typeData.textContent:
This psychology course will introduce you to some of the major research areas within the field of psychology: the scientific study of behaviour.  The course begins with an overview of psychology and its research methods, and then covers several fundamental topics in psychology such as biological psychology, learning and memory, and conscious states.

This section of PSYC101 is a 3-credit online distance education course.  It has both synchronous (live; e.g., Q&A sessions, discussion sessions, and group activities) and asynchronous  components (not live; e.g., prerecorded lectures, online quizzes, and self-assessments).  Because it is a distance education course, most course-related activities are asynchronous.

The course uses an open-source text that is supplemented by many video-based lectures and online resources. In addition, the course contains interviews with some leading research psychologists and some educational animations.

There are no prerequisites or corequisites for this course.  Note that you cannot receive credit for both PSYC101 and PSYC100.

nodes.title: Anatomy of a Typical Synapse (Alyssa Juma)
Week 7 – The Epigenetics of Childhood Trauma (Sherry Wang)

typeData.textContent:
Some external factors such as diet, drugs and chemicals are capable of turning genes on or off without modifying the basic DNA sequences. Such changes in gene expression are heritable and can be passed on to several generations. This is the so-called epigenetics.

There is a series of studies showing that epigenetics plays an important role in the persisting effects of early experiences. Serious stressors, especially early in life, can change the phenotypes and have long-lasting effects on both physical and mental health. Much of this work was done by Michael Meaney and his colleagues at McGill University.

Maternal behaviors in rats

Their first experiment examines the effects that different mothering styles have on baby rats. There are two groups of mother rats, one spends much time licking their pups, which is called “high lickers”, whereas the other one spends little time doing so, which is called “low lickers”. The researchers found that highly licked rat pups are much less fearful and have better control of stress as adults when placed in a stressful environment. The rising level of serotonin in pups leads to a decrease in DNA methylation, which regulates the level of cortisol, a stress hormone, and helps them to get back to normal quickly.

Childhood abuse

Such long-term impact of childhood experiences not only exists in rats but also humans. In a recent study, Meaney’s team extracted the hippocampal samples of 12 men who committed suicide when they were 35 years old and had the experience of childhood abuse, and 12 men who committed suicide when they were 35 years old but with no experience of childhood abuse. The researchers separated them into two groups and compared each group with a control group of 12 men who died at around the same age but had no experience of abuse and suicide. The results showed that the level of DNA methylation of the group who had a history of abuse and committed suicide had increased compared to others, while there was no significant difference between the other two groups, regardless of whether they died of suicide.

To sum up, childhood trauma can actually influence our gene expression and result in a higher risk of developing mental and physical health problems later in life. Therefore, adults should endeavor to create a safe and warm family environment, which will protect not only their children but also the following generations.

Reference

https://www.psychologytoday.com/ca/blog/psyched/201909/the-epigenetics-childhood-trauma-0

https://www.mcgill.ca/newsroom/channels/news/childhood-trauma-has-life-long-effect-genes-and-brain-104667

McGowan, P. O., Sasaki, A., D’Alessio, A. C., Dymov, S., Labonté, B., Szyf, M., Turecki, G., & Meaney, M. J. (2009). Epigenetic regulation of the glucocorticoid receptor in human brain associates with childhood abuse. Nature neuroscience, 12(3), 342–348. https://doi.org/10.1038/nn.2270

Types of Pitch Perception
nodes.description: There are different types of pitch perception in our auditory system.

typeData.textContent:
Temporal theory of pitch perception: frequency is coded by the activity level of a sensory neuron. A given hair cell would fire action potentials related to the frequency of the sound wave. 
- detect such a broad range of frequencies (20–20,000 Hz) that the frequency of action potentials fired by hair cells cannot account for the entire range.
-Because of properties related to sodium channels on the neuronal membrane that are involved in action potentials, there is a point at which a cell cannot fire any faster

Place theory: different portions of the basilar membrane are sensitive to sounds of different frequencies
-base of the basilar membrane responds best to high frequencies and the tip of the basilar membrane responds best to low frequencies.
-hair cells that are in the base portion would be labeled as high-pitch receptors, while those in the tip of basilar membrane would be labeled as low-pitch receptors

Both theories explain different aspects of pitch perception. Much higher frequency sounds can only be encoded using place cues

nodes.title: Inattentional Blindness Activity Primer
nodes.description: A description of the next node's test.

typeData.textContent:
Inattentional blindness can happen to anyone, regardless of cognitive abilities, as was mentioned earlier. This is often surprising for people to learn, because it is almost impossible to notice what you fail to perceive. As such, many people probably experience inattentional blindness frequently and don't notice. There is still an ongoing debate over the causes of inattentional blindness, and scientists use certain experiments in order to find the conditions under which inattentional blindness occurs. In the next node, you will be invited to participate in an activity that can help you become aware of your own inattentional blindness.

In the next node, you will be presented with a video, then a few questions. Watch the video first, then proceed to the questions. Please do not read the questions first. Please follow the video's instructions carefully. Note that the activity will not be as effective if the instructions in the video aren't followed. After you are done, feel free to explore the rest of our nodes about the potential causes and effects of inattentional blindness.

nodes.title: Causes of Inattentional Blindness (Simran Rai)
nodes.description: Causes

typeData.textContent:
Inattentional Blindness Video Debriefing

In the previous node, you watched an interactive video that allowed you to see the effects of inattentional blindness firsthand. During the video, you might have kept your focus on the ball to see how many times it was passed around by the team wearing white. This focus might have caused you to ignore the person wearing the bear costume dance across the court. The purpose of this video was to show how we are often unable to detect changes in our visual field when focused on a certain task, which results in a form of selective attention called inattentional blindness. There are many reasons that inattentional blindness can occur, such as…


Attention/Perception

- people are more likely to notice meaningful stimuli rather than less meaningful stimuli since it is more likely to capture their attention.

- attention is vital in enabling perception as well as suppressing it. An individual can perceive something in their visual field if they are paying attention to it. Likewise, if they are not consciously paying attention to specific stimuli, they may not be able to perceive or process what it is they are seeing. 


Colors/Shape

- people may display inattentional blindness when focusing on distinct colors or patterns. For example, in the video you watched, you focused on the players wearing white and not the ones wearing black. So, you may have ignored the person in the bear costume based on the assumption that it was another player. 

- the brightness of certain stimuli also has an impact on what we allow to be unconsciously processed by our visual field.

Sources: 
https://www.apa.org/monitor/apr01/blindness
https://www2.psych.ubc.ca/~rensink/publications/download/EncycConsc-CB-IB-rr.pdf

nodes.title: The Importance of Taste (Fallon Furkalo)
nodes.description: Summary on the importance of taste and some studies on impaired sense of taste.

typeData.textContent:
The sense of taste has been on the sidelines compared to its other sense counterparts. However, the sense of taste is much more important than people have originally thought it to be. Taste is one of the most life-essential senses. If the sense of taste is impaired, there can be many detrimental consequences because of it. Impairment of taste can negatively affect an individual's food intake, nutritional status, and overall health condition. The sense of taste is very important in identifying important nutrients in one’s environment and procuring the right amount of energy in order for one to survive. 

There have been studies within dentistry focused on finding links between taste and behaviour, neurology, cancer, and rheumatic diseases. One study was focusing on Sjögren's syndrome and taste. Sjögren's syndrome is an autoimmune disease (immune system attacks parts of one’s body by mistake) that attacks the tear and saliva making glands leading to dry mouth and eyes. The study found that people with Sjögren's syndrome have an impaired sense of taste, meaning it is reduced or distorted from what it was before. 

Researchers have also taken an interest in researching whether dental treatment can affect taste. However, there aren’t any major results yet from these studies. Dr. Singh is investigating how the sense of taste and smell are affected in patients with cancer. She is involved in two studies, one at NYU in the Department of Oral and Maxillofacial Surgery and another at the surgical department of the Norwegian Radium Hospital. At NYU, she is investigating with others the occurrences of a disturbed sense of taste in individuals with oral cavity cancer. At the Norwegian Radium Hospital, she is investigating with others the occurrence of a disturbed sense of taste and smell in cancer survivors.

Bjørkeng, A. (2018, July 02). Senses of taste and smell more important than we think. Retrieved
July 27, 2020, from https://medicalxpress.com/news/2018-07-important.html

nodes.title: The Receptors of the Somatosensory System. (Jessica Groening)
nodes.description: This is a summary of the different receptors found within the somatosensory system with several examples.

typeData.textContent:
The somatosensory system is composed of many different types of receptors which transduce specific types of mechanical stimuli. These receptors will help with interoceptive (inside the body), proprioceptive (joints and muscles), and cutaneous/exteroceptive (outside of the body; e.g. the skin) sensitivity. Exteroceptive receptors may help the body notice changes in the external environment which may include pressure, vibration, texture, temperature, pain, and itch. 

The different receptors of the somatosensory system include the following. 

1.	Mechanoreceptors; these receptor types will transduce sensory information related to mechanical stimulation or pressure. There are several specific types of mechanoreceptors which transduce these types of cutaneous sensations. These exteroceptive receptors include the Meissner’s corpuscles (pressure and lower frequency vibrations), the Pacinian corpuscles (transient pressure and higher frequency vibrations), Merkel’s disks (light pressure), and the Ruffini corpuscles (stretch). Furthermore, there are specialized, interoceptive mechanoreceptors known as kinesthetic receptors. These are found within the muscles, tendons, and joints. They are responsible for determining the position and movement of various parts of the body. E.g. they will help you when bringing a cup up to your mouth to drink. Instead of dumping the cup on your shoulder, the kinesthetic receptors will guide the movement of the cup to your lips.

2.	Thermoreceptors; these receptors are involved in the detection of changes in temperature on the skin. They can be divided further into warmth fibers and cold fibers, and this helps the body with the interpretation of the specific temperature. For example, when you place your hand into an ice bath, the cold fibers will respond and indicate that there is a cold sensation on the skin.

3.	Nociceptors; these receptor types are involved in the experience of painful stimuli, that has the potential to cause damage to the skin. These receptors are very important in keeping the organism safe and reducing injury to the body. E.g. if you stepped on a sharp rock, the nociceptors would transduce the information of pain to the brain, and this would result in you moving your foot away from the rock in order to prevent damage. There is a condition, known as congenital insensitivity to pain, where the nociceptors of the body do not function correctly. These individuals will feel pressure, though they are unable to experience pain. Therefore, this is particularly dangerous as they will be more prone to injury.

nodes.title: Olfactory Sensation Explained (Aaron Dokiburra)
nodes.description: Explanation of the Olfactory system.

typeData.textContent:
The sense of smell is an important sense for humans. For detecting danger such as a gas leak and recalling past smells through emotions and memory in the brain.

1. The sensation of different smells is first received by small hair-like extensions on the structure called – Olfactory Bulb in the nose cavity.

2. When an odor enters the cavity, it is dissolved within the mucus.

3. The dissolved odor substances bond onto a receptor.

4. Chemical changes occur within the cell and the signal gets sent to the olfactory bulb.

5. The olfactory bulb is at the tip of the frontal lobe and info is sent to the brain: the limbic system and primary olfactory cortex.

6. The info is then processed and received by different regions as well as regions for memory and emotions.

Broad Implications of Inattentional Blindness (Catherine Huang)
nodes.description: Here are some examples of inattentional blindness that occur in our daily lives.

typeData.textContent:
As we've learned from the previous node and the gorilla experiment, there are many factors that play into inattentional blindness. But we don't have to look at laboratory experiments to understand this phenomenon. Inattentional blindness occurs in a variety of ways in our everyday lives.

Distracted Driving
Recent studies have found that when a person's attention is focussed on another object or task, he/she will tend to experience inattentional blindness. This means that texting, navigating, calling, reading maps and even eating while driving can cause tragic accidents. While we may want to think we are good multitaskers, the matter of fact is that we aren't.

Unaware Students
In a study by Ira Hymen, it was discovered that students that used their cellphones (calling, texting, listening to music) while walking on campus were less likely to notice even the most unusual events around them—like a unicycling clown. Keep your eyes peeled; you'll never know what exciting things will show up on campus!
As we’ve learned from the previous node and the gorilla experiment, there are many factors that play into inattentional blindness. But we don’t have to look at laboratory experiments to understand this phenomenon. Inattentional blindness occurs in a variety of ways in our everyday lives.

Careless Work?
In one incident, the Pennsylvania highway crew paved over a dead deer lying on the ground. The crew claimed that they had not seen the deer even though the mayor claims that it was in plain sight.

Sources:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inattentional_blindness#Broader_implications
https://apnews.com/0377a3e7b5ffd67e450980e275cb1f84
https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/acp.1638

nodes.title: Types of Attention Encountered by Humans (Harper Gibson

typeData.textContent:
Types of attention encountered by humans 

	Everyone has experienced days where they seem to struggle with attention in class, conversations, and other daily aspects of life.  On the other hand, we have also experienced times where we feel as though others are purposely ignoring us.  In this node, I will go over the processes and types of attention that explain why these things happen to us on a regular basis.

	Selective attention is a term used to describe when there is a lot going on around us, but we only tend to hear what we consider important in that moment.  For example, if you are having a conversation with someone in a busy place, you tend to tune out all of the background noise because you are focused on your conversation.  This works in the opposite direction as well, if you are trying to get someone’s attention while they are busy doing something else, the chances are they will not notice you at first.  

	There are two types of attention, endogenous and exogenous.  Endogenous means something that has an internal cause therefore in this case one’s decision to pay attention to something comes from within the person.  For example if a person chooses to look at their phone without any notifications on it, this would be considered endogenous.  Exogenous means something that has an external cause therefore there would have to be some sort of stimulus to provoke a person’s attention.  An example of this would be if a person’s cell phone started ringing, and the ringing caused the person to look at it.  These two types of attention can also be referred to as top-down (endogenous) attention and bottom-up (exogenous) attention.

	Endogenous attention can be split even further into two groups, volitional and mandatory.  Both of these still come from within however there are slight differences between the two.  Volitional attention can be described as voluntary attention which brings us back to the example of checking a phone, even though there are no notifications.  Mandatory attention refers to something that you will notice, not by choice but because it is your nature to notice it.  For example, if you have ever seen optical illusions where an image can appear as multiple different objects, your mandatory attention is what is causing you to see both.  

	The last type of attention that I will go over is inattentional blindness.  This addresses how one will not notice a very noticeable object if one is focused on another.  Daniel Simmons tested this hypothesis by telling individuals to focus on a screen and count the number of times a ball was passed from person to person, meanwhile a person in a gorilla costume walked across the screen.  The result of this video is that when focused on counting how many time the ball was passed, the gorilla went unnoticed because all attention was focused on the ball being passed.

Week 9: Gate Theory of Pain (Erin Cheng)
nodes.description: A theory suggesting the existence of a "gate system" in our spinal cord that regulates pain and sensory systems.

typeData.textContent:
What is it: 

First proposed in 1965 by Ronald Melzack and Patrik Wall, the gate control theory of pain suggests that we have a neurological “gate” in our central nervous system that could open or close to allow pain signals through to the brain. 

How it works: 

Once we experience an injury, sensory receptors in our skin will send signals to our spinal cord to be transmitted to our brain. The gate theory suggests that prior to reaching the brain, pain signals encounter “nerve gates” in the spinal cord that can control whether or not to amplify, minimize, or block out these signals.

This mechanism occurs in the dorsal horn of our spinal cord. The dorsal horn receives information from both small nerve fibres that carry pain signals and large nerve fibres that transmit regular sensory information such as touch and pressure. The large nerve fibres that carry normal touch information have the ability to diminish pain signals from the small nerve fibres. When there is more large nerve fibre activity as to small nerve fibre activity, inhibitory neurons get activated and closes the “gate” in your dorsal horn, delaying the pain signals from getting to your brain. An example would be if you bang your shin against a chair and begin rubbing it, the sensory information from the rubbing will temporarily inhibit the pain signal from travelling to the brain. However, if there is more small fibre nerve activity, the pain signals will impede the inhibitory neurons, allowing the pain information to travel to your brain through the now open “gates”.

Spinal Cord Gray Matter Anatomy
Issues with the theory: 

Although the gate theory of pain attracted a lot of attention and encouraged many more studies that furthered our understanding of pain, there is insufficient evidence to prove the existence of a gating system in the spinal cord.

typeData.textContent:
When talking about the auditory system, there are a few terms that must be defined: 

1. Frequency: perception of pitch, measured by pitch wavelength
Low frequency waves are associated with low-pitched sounds
High frequency waves are associated with high-pitched sounds

2. Amplitude: perception of loudness. 
High amplitude waves are associated with loud sounds 
Low amplitude waves are associated with soft sounds 

3. Complexity: perception of timbre
Simple waves have a pure tone 
Complex waves have a mix of frequency, said to be high in timbre

ANATOMY OF THE EAR: 
The ear is comprised of three main areas: 
1. Outer ear:
The ear drum (found in the outer ear) converts sounds in the air into physical motion. This physical motion deflects bones in the: 

2. Middle ear: 
The small bones in the middle ear are called ossicles. They connect the ear drum to the cochlea (where they cause fluid change). 

3. Inner ear: 
The cochlea is the major component of the inner ear. It is a tightly wound structure with two ends. 1) The oval window end is where the ossicles bang on when the ear drum is activated by sound, as mentioned previously and 2) the apex, where the basilar membrane is located.

Selective attention refers to the cognitive ability to filter out sensory information in favour of the relevant.

ENDOGENOUS ATTENTION (top-down processes)
- internal decisions; checking the time involves the internal decision to look at a clock
- 2 types:
	o volitional (decisions)
	o mandatory (neural machinery, it automatically occurs out of your control)

EXOGENOUS ATTENTION (bottom-up processes)
- external stimuli; a classmate dropping a pencil during a test involves an auditory signal directing your attention to the stimulus, the pencil

CHANGE BLINDNESS
- it is very difficult to notice a difference between a previous state and a current state
	o if an image is displayed on a screen for 4 seconds, followed by a grey screen, a different image is displayed, followed by a grey screen, first image is shown again and so forth, viewers have great difficulty finding differences between the images

INATTENTIONAL BLINDNESS
- we are unaware of things in our environment that we do not pay direct attention to
	o Daniel Simons et al.'s gorilla experiment tells viewers to count how many times a ball is passed, but they fail to see a person dressed up in a gorilla suit wandering across the screen

nodes.title: Pain and Congenital Insensitivity to Pain (Lindsay Anta)

typeData.textContent:
Pain and Congenital Insensitivity to Pain (CIP)

	Congenital insensitivity to pain is a condition of the peripheral nervous system in which the individual can not perceive physical pain. This is an extremely rare condition caused a recessive gene mutation. To understand this condition, we must first understand how people typically can experience pain.

	There are many receptors that work in our peripheral nervous system which allows our bodies to interact with the world around us. Nociceptors are the receptors that respond to pain, and they report any noxious stimuli that can result in bodily harm to the brain. In the typical human body, pain can come from a variety of stimuli, from simply tripping or stubbing your toe to life threatening injuries. Pain is a very subjective experience, as everyone has a different tolerance of discomfort, but we all have the same pain threshold, meaning at the same point all of our nociceptors can be activated at the same amount of painful stimuli. This is all meant to protect our tissues and nerves from potentially permanent damage. 
	
	But in some people, they can not feel pain at all. This is a result of a condition that stops them from perceiving pain. There are multiple types of this condition caused by different gene mutations, but among the most common is CIP, or congenital insensitivity to pain, caused by a mutation of the SCN9A gene. People with CIP do not receive the same signals that tell us to get our hand off the stove because it is burning our skin because they cannot tell that it is burning unless they can see the damage themselves. The SCN9A gene impacts a sodium channel called Nav1.7, which results in a lack of action potentials in the nerves of the peripheral nervous system. If the action potentials stop then the signal of pain does not reach the brain. This is a rare condition, so much of the research of this condition is not fully developed and it is possible that this condition is so rare because many children with CIP do not reach adulthood because of the injuries they typically sustain. CIP also causes the person’s nociceptors to be completely nonfunctional or to be underdeveloped and in some cases, they also have anosmia, or the inability to smell. CIP is a difficult condition to live with, as the individual has lost the natural protection of pain and this often will take a psychological toll on that person.

What happens when you lose somatosensory receptors (Anika Morokhovich)

typeData.textContent:
Losing somatosensory receptors can have a huge effect on your body and life. 

The inability to form nociceptors results in congenital insensitivity to pain. People with this condition cannot experience pain. They can distinguish between hot and cold and dull or sharp pain but cannot physically sense the pain. This can cause a lot of damages and injury without the person knowing. This disease can greatly shorten the lifespan of an individual. 

Without thermoreceptors your body is not able to sense temperature. Since your body cannot sense the outside temperature it becomes very difficult for your hypothalamus to regulate your body. Thermoreceptors are very important for thermoregulation and living without them could have bad consequences. 

The loss of kinesthetic receptors causes you to be unaware of your own body and its movements. This can occur from diseases or from injuries. When the loss of kinesthetics begins to occur, it would make walking or simply moving your fingers without looking very difficult. It is possible to retrain yourself to look intently at your body while you move it. This allows people with loss of the kinesthetics receptors the ability to still move around.

nodes.title: A Better Understanding of the Phenomenons of Selective Attention (Julie Lam)

typeData.textContent:
There are two main perceptual phenomenons in the realm of selective attention. They are change blindness and inattentional blindness. Both are failures of visual awareness.

Change blindness is the failure to notice obvious changes when it is introduced to a visual stimulus. Distractions, interruptions, and shifts in attention often increase the chance of change blindness. In addition, speed is also a factor as instantaneous changes in visual details are more easily masked by fast interruptions. Smaller factors that could also influence change blindness include age, attention, the presentation of objects, and the use of psychoactive drugs.

Some techniques that can be used to minimize change blindness are:
1) Minimizing visual interruptions
2) Focusing and emphasizing on new significant elements

Inattentional blindness is the failure to notice the existence of a fully-visible but unexpected object when attention is focused on another task, event, or object. This happens as concentration is usually utilized on things that are the most important, resulting in the reliance on existing schemas to contribute to the rest of the visual stimulus. 

Some techniques that can be used to minimize inattentional blindness are:
1) Increasing the conspicuity of important information
2) Decreasing diversions of attention
3) Reducing the number of secondary tasks when carrying out complex tasks

Auditory System Summary and important terms (Elbert Ng)
nodes.description: Please read and then answer the quiz.

typeData.textContent:
This is a Summary of the important points, terms and definitions to remember about the auditory system.

Pinna: Part of the outer ear which protrudes out from our head.

Tympanic membrane/Eardrum: Sound waves first vibrate this part of the ear, and then in turn the eardrum helps in the movement of the three ossicles.

Malleus/Hammer: The first part of the three ossicles. Sound vibrates through the malleus first.

Incus/Anvil: The second part of the three ossicles. Sound vibrates through the incus after the malleus.

Stapes/Stirrup: The last part of the three ossicles. The stapes is connected to the oval window near the cochlea.

Cochlea: a fluid-filled and conch shaped structure that contains the sensory receptor cells. Contains the basilar membrane.

Semicircular canals: Involved in balance and movement (Vestibular sense)

Temporal theory of pitch perception: States that different frequencies are determined by the different firing rates of the neuron.

Place theory of pitch perception:States that different portions of the basilar membrane are sensitive to different sounds with different frequencies; the base of the basilar membrane responds best to high frequencies and the tip of the basilar membrane responds best to low frequencies.

Interaural level difference: When a sound is more intense at one side of the ear more than the other due to attenuation when the sound wave crosses through your head.

Interaural timing difference: The small difference in time at which the sounds arrive at each ear.

Congenital deafness: People who are born deaf.

Sensorineural hearing loss: When the cochlea fails to transmit neural signals to the brain.

Conductive hearing loss: When vibration of the eardrum fails or the movement of ossicles does not happen.

Frequency: Corresponds to the pitch. Higher frequency means higher pitch.

Amplitude: Corresponds to the loudness. HIgher amplitude means louder.

Complexity: Corresponds to the timbre: More complex means better timbre.

The receptor cells of the auditory system are located in the cochlea, more specifically it is the hair cells (stereocilia) embedded in the basilar membrane. The information is transduced when the mechanical energy from the shear force brushing the stereocilia cells is converted into neural information.

Tonotopic organization: It is found in the cochlea and the primary auditory cortex (A1). When the cells for certain frequencies of sound are found in a position such that there exists a standard relationship between position and frequency. Similar to the place theory.

Presbycusis: As a person gets older, their sensitivity towards high frequency sounds is decreased.

typeData.textContent: Inattentional blindness is a phenomenon of failure to detect unexpected objects that attention is not engaged on. It can occur when a strong focus is on another subject, resulting in complete blindness towards a stimulus that is plain in sight. However, this most often occurs during multisensory, multitasking activities. A very common activity that influences many lives day to day is the act of driving; driving requires focus on multiple things at once--keeping eye on the road while also periodically checking the rearview mirror as well as maintaining speed limit and staying within the lanes and noticing traffic lights, incoming traffic, other cars, and pedestrians. The abundance of tasks in addition to the overload of stimuli could easily result in inattentional blindness. Examples would be that while an individual is focused on the road and keeping to the speed limit, they could possibly 'not see' the stop sign approaching ahead even though their eyes are focused on the road and the sign can clearly be seen. This can also happen when attempting to turn left at a busy intersection, while one is focused on the incoming traffic, they might not notice the pedestrians crossing the road which can result in a, potentially fatal, accident. Although this phenomenon can affect anyone, steps can be taken to minimize it, especially when performing potentially dangerous tasks; such as pausing a conversation with a passenger when trying to turn in a busy intersection, avoid phone usage, and familiarize yourself with your car's equipment to be comfortable adjusting the car's features without losing focus on the road. Small distractions can easily lead to big accidents, if you're not careful.

nodes.description: selective attention

typeData.textContent:
Selective attention is the process of directing our awareness to relevant stimuli while ignoring irrelevant stimuli in the environment.This is an important process because it is impossible to pay attention to all information at a given time, so we use selective attention to ignore insignificant details and focus on the important things.For example, you listen carefully to what someone is saying while ignoring other conversations in a room. 
There are two forms of attention, which are known as endogenous attention (top-down processes) and exogenous attention (bottom-up processes). Endogenous attention is driven by internal goals, while exogenous attention refers to effects that are generated externally by the physical properties of stimuli.

nodes.title: Kinesthetic Receptors, Nociceptors and Phantom Limbs (Harjot Gill)
nodes.description: Short story

typeData.textContent:
Imagine you are driving to work on a cold winter day. Snow is falling and the road ahead of you is difficult to see. Suddenly you hit a patch of ice and your car swerves and hits a large oak tree. Minutes pass as your heart rate begins to slow. The driver side door is slightly crushed in but everything seems okay and you feel okay. While looking around you notice your hand is stuck between the indented door and steering wheel. You slowly try to loosen your hand and then you realize that your hand is crushed. You begin to feel excruciating pain and the image of your mutilated hand is something you will never forget. Later on in the hospital you are told your hand needs to be amputated.

From the moment you lost control of the car to post amputation of your hand, there are many receptors in your body that helped you understand what was occurring. These receptors are part of your somatosensory system. One of the very first receptors would be the kinesthetic receptors that felt your body jerk in the wrong direction when the car skid on the ice. Kinesthetic receptors are a type of mechanoreceptor (respond to mechanical stimulation or pressure) that are present within our muscles, tendons and joints. Kinesthetic receptors help us interpret where our limbs are and the types of movements made by our body. From stimulation of these receptors you were able to realize you were going in a different direction. These receptors also help you realize where your hand was when it was stuck between the door and steering wheel. Being able to sense where your limbs are in space helped you realize what was happening to your body.

In addition to the kinesthetic receptors, your nociceptors helped you realize that your hand was in pain. Nociceptors respond to painful stimuli and when there is silumi that can cause or does cause damage to the skin, they transmit information to the body and brain. The stimulation from your hand being crushed activated your nociceptors to make you understand what was occurring to your hand. As you removed your hand and saw what had happened to it, the pain you felt and the image of your crushed hand will never leave your brain. A few years down the road after your hand amputation this can lead to phantom limb syndrome. This is a sensation of having a limb that is no longer attached to your body and you may begin to feel the type of pain from when it was injured or experience contractions in the limb. To help treat phantom limbs, showing the intact phantom limb in a normal position or non crushed state can help elevate the pain. This can be done by putting a mirror in front of your intact hand so you see the reflection of your intact hand where your phantom limb would be.

Hitting the tree on a cold winter day may have changed your life however many receptors along the way helped you realize what was occurring. Kinesthetic receptors and nociceptors made sure that a bad accident was not worse than it already was.

Receptor Types (Jules Clark)
nodes.description: Welcome to Receptor Types and Their Functions for this weeks content

typeData.textContent:
Receptor Types and Their Functions (Jules Clark)
Our bodies have an abundant number of receptors that all have there very own function; no two receptors are the same. Understanding the many receptors and the role they play in maintaining our bodies homeostasis is not only important, but surprisingly cool. 
Within the Somatosensory system we have a number of receptors that detect pressures, pains, temperatures, positions, movements and vibrations and send a signals to sensory nerves.
1) Mechanoreceptors: These are receptors on our skin that respond to mechanical stimulation or pressure changes.  
2) Kinesthetic receptors: These receptors are found within our muscles, joints and tendons and help us detect where ones limbs are and what kinds of movements are being made.
3) Thermoreceptors: These receptors are also found on the skin and they detect heat and cold on the skin.
4) Nociceptors: These receptors are also known as pain receptors due to their function in detecting potentially damaging stimuli. When a harmful threat it detected they send possible threat signals to the brain and stimuli. 
This concludes the various receptors and their functions within the somatosensory system. 

Olfactory (smell) Receptors: These are also known as odorant receptors and are responsible for detecting different odors. There are approximately 300 receptors within this system that all have receptor proteins at the tip of their dendrites. These receptor proteins are what the chemical stimuli (different odors) bind to to be converted into a neural signal sent to the Central Nervous System. 

Gustatory (Taste) Receptors: Within the gustatory system there are approximately 34 receptor protiens; 1 umami (savory), 2 sweet, 30 bitter and 1 salty receptor. On the tongue we have papillae (tiny bumps that are larger at the back and get smaller closer to the tip of the tongue). These papillae consist of taste buds which contain the taste receptors. 

Auditory Receptors: The auditory receptors are actually the hair cells themselves. The hair cells line the Organ of Corti within the cochlea. The hair cells release neurotransmitter from their base into the basal end of the hair cell. This stimulates an electrical signal along the cochlea to produce sound.

nodes.title: Proprioceptive Sensations related to somatosensory system (Ziyue Song)
nodes.description: Proprioception refers to the sense of knowing how one’s body is positioned in three-dimensional space.

typeData.textContent:
Proprioception is the perception of the relative position of adjacent parts of the body and the force used in the movement. It is different from the external sensation, pain, hunger, internal movement and so on.
The initiation of proprioception refers to the activation of proprioceptors on the outer edge. Proprioception is thought to consist of information about sensory neurons (movement and direction) in the inner ear and stretch receptors (stretching receptors) in the muscles and joints supporting the ligaments (standing).
Conscious proprioception is transmitted to the brain by the posterior (dorsal) column-medial thalamus pathway. Unconscious proprioception is mainly transmitted to the cerebellum through the dorsal and ventral spinal cord.
An unconscious response can be seen in the human proprioception reflex. When leaning in any direction, the person will tilt his head back so that his eyes are level with the horizon. This can happen even after babies gain control of their neck muscles. This control comes from the cerebellum, the part of the brain that affects balance.
Muscle spindles are sensory receptors located in the abdomen of a muscle. They are used to detect changes in muscle length. They transmit length information to the central nervous system via sensory neurons. The brain can process this information to determine the location of body parts. The response of the muscle spindle to changes in length also plays an important role in regulating muscle contraction.

nodes.title: Gestalt Perception in Non-Sight Senses (Anirudh Kannan)
nodes.description: In this node, I’ll explore how Gestalt ideas apply to senses other than sight, primarily hearing.

typeData.textContent:
PSYC 101 – Week 9 Tapestry – Non-H5P Node:
Name: Anirudh Kannan
Student Number: 58094780
Group name: kagbiological 


In this node, I’ll explore how Gestalt ideas apply to senses other than sight, primarily hearing. 

Hearing:
Firstly, even to a layperson, one can quickly see that, to a perceptible extent, sound is perceived in a Gestalt fashion, i.e. the whole is qualitatively different to the sum of the parts. The ‘parts’ that constitute sounds are a.) sound b.) lack of sound; to use a specific example, music is comprised of notes and lack of notes, and yet it’s perceived as a symphonic, magnificent whole that’s qualitatively different to the objective stimuli, which are a series of notes separated by pauses.

There are a number of heuristics, analogous to the ‘rules’ we saw in the textbook that concerned visual perception, that dictate how auditory signals are perceived. 

The proximity rule applies for sound; sounds that are proximal in timing or frequency tend to be grouped together [1]. A corollary of this is that sounds that begin and end simultaneously are also grouped together. Apparently, spatial location is not a factor that affects auditory proximity [1], in contrast to visual proximity, which is almost exclusively determined by spatial location. 

One model that attempts to summarize how Gestalt principles play a part in hearing is comprised of two steps [2]:
1.	Segregation
2.	Grouping.

The argument is that much of the Gestalt heuristics that are used by our auditory system exist and function in service of one of these two steps [2]. 

Furthermore, the attempt to find an auditory analogue for the figure-ground relationship yields an interesting observation: figure-ground segregation in hearing is not automatic (rather, it relies on deliberate directed attention), and borrows cues from the visual system too [3]. 

In the same way as we ‘close’ shapes that aren’t really there when perceiving visually, we also are able to ‘restore’ parts of a sound that have been hidden by a louder sound. When performed by the auditory system, this is known as “auditory induction” [4]. 

Lastly, the Gestalt principle of ‘common fate’, which states that objects that simultaneously change in the same way are bound to be grouped together, also has an auditory analogue. Acoustic components that exhibit changes in amplitude (ostensibly in the same direction) are grouped together by the hearing system [4]. 

Touch:
Apparently, many studies directly or indirectly hint that the principles of proximity, similarity, common fate, continuation, and closure affect not only auditory and visual perception, but also tactile perception [5]. 

Gustation:
It has also been hypothesised that the ability to say that something “tastes like X” is evidence of Gestalt principles at play in our palates, because the ability to relate two tastes requires a perception of the whole of the taste, as it were, and not necessarily an appreciation of the components that constitute the tastes [6]. 

Olfactory:
There is even limited evidence that analogous laws exist to aid olfactoral perception [7].

2.	https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6358108/
3.	https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Figure%E2%80%93ground_(perception)
4.	http://spandh.dcs.shef.ac.uk/research/asa.html
5.	https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22774798/
